PM Ticket Management Rules
1. Keep Linear Tickets Updated Regularly
All project work must be tracked and updated in Linear to ensure transparency, alignment, and predictable delivery.

2. What Needs to Be Updated
2.1 Maintain Active Work
Each team member should always have at least one ticket in progress when they are actively working on a project.


This helps PMs and stakeholders understand current workload and progress.
Move the ticket to the backlog when working on other tasks. 


2.2 Ownership & Update Cadence
The ticket owner is responsible for keeping the ticket accurate and up to date.


Tickets must be reviewed and updated at least every two days (status, progress, blockers, or notes).


2.3 Required Dates
Every ticket must include:


Start Date


End Date / Target Completion Date


These fields should be filled at the time of ticket creation.


2.4 Document Progress in Comments
Use the comment section to record:


Key updates or milestones


Decisions made


Blockers or risks


Links to PRs, docs, or related resources


Comments should reflect meaningful progress, not minor step-by-step logs.
2.5 Ticket Scope & Sizing
A ticket should represent roughly one week of work.


Avoid tickets that are:


❌ Too small (micro-tasks that create noise)


❌ Too large (unclear scope or multi-week efforts)


If work exceeds one week, split it into smaller deliverables.

2.6 Additional Best Practices
• Use **clear, descriptive titles** that summarize the outcome (avoid vague words like “fix” or “update”).
• Add a short **acceptance criteria** or definition of done in the description so reviewers know when the ticket is complete.
• Apply appropriate **labels** (feature, bug, improvement, etc.) and set the correct **priority** when the ticket is created.
• Link all relevant **PRs, documents, designs, and demo recordings** in the description or comments.
• When closing a ticket, add a final comment summarizing what changed and reference the merged PR or deployment.
• Delete or archive stale tickets; move in‑progress items to backlog if they’ve been inactive for more than two weeks.
• Use the “blocks/blocked by” relations where dependencies exist to give visibility into cross‑ticket impact.
